# chaos-overlay.env — the resilience knobs the live-stack chaos lane
# patches onto the cerberus-config ConfigMap before fault injection.
#
# Applied by .github/scripts/chaos-run.mjs via `kubectl set env deploy/cerberus`
# (one key=value per non-comment line below) so the faults trip FAST and
# DETERMINISTICALLY within the per-scenario budget, instead of the
# production-shaped defaults that would take minutes to converge.
#
# Why each value differs from the baked-in test/e2e/k3s/cerberus.yaml default:
#
#   CERBERUS_CH_BREAKER_THRESHOLD=3
#     Default 5. A lower consecutive-failure trip count means the
#     ch-pod-kill / ch-network-partition scenarios force the shared breaker
#     OPEN with a SHORTER tight query loop — fewer requests to drive, less
#     wall-clock in the during-fault window, less chance the fault heals
#     before the trip lands.
#
#   CERBERUS_CH_BREAKER_WINDOW=10s
#     Default 10s — restated explicitly so the trip arithmetic
#     (THRESHOLD failures within WINDOW) is self-documenting in the lane.
#
#   CERBERUS_CH_BREAKER_OPEN_INTERVAL=5s
#     Default 5s — restated so the HALF-OPEN recovery probe cadence the
#     recovery poll waits on is explicit.
#
#   CERBERUS_QUERY_TIMEOUT=3s
#     Default 2m. A small wall-clock cap is what the ch-slow/query-timeout
#     scenario PROVES fires: a heavy query blows past 3s and is aborted with
#     CH TIMEOUT_EXCEEDED (code 159), surfacing as the clean 503
#     errorType=timeout the contract pins. The query drives cost via COMPUTE
#     PER ANCHOR — a nested subquery (max_over_time over a sub-stepped
#     rate()) fanned out at every outer anchor — NOT via anchor count: a
#     wide range with a tiny step (millions of anchors) would be rejected by
#     cerberus's 11000-point resolution guard with a 400 before the timeout
#     ever arms (the guard runs first, by design — it mirrors upstream
#     Prometheus). See slowQueryPath / the SLOW_QUERY_* constants in
#     .github/scripts/chaos-run.mjs. 2m would make the scenario take minutes;
#     3s keeps it inside the budget while staying well above the 1s /readyz
#     ping so readiness is unaffected.
#
#   CERBERUS_ADMIT_PROM=2
#   CERBERUS_ADMIT_LOKI=2
#   CERBERUS_ADMIT_TEMPO=2
#     Default is the binary's CPU-derived cap (tens). A tiny in-flight cap
#     means the load/admit-saturation scenario reaches the shed threshold
#     with a handful of concurrent requests — deterministic 503 +
#     Retry-After:1 'server saturated' + cerberus_admit_rejected_total
#     {reason=cap_exceeded} within budget, rather than needing hundreds of
#     concurrent clients to overwhelm a production-sized cap.
#
#   CERBERUS_CH_MAX_OPEN_CONNS=4
#     Default 10. A small pool corroborates that pool-acquire timeouts are
#     breaker-NEUTRAL under the same saturation burst (a too-small pool
#     must never trip CH health). Kept >= the admit cap so admission, not
#     the pool, is the first-order shed signal.
CERBERUS_CH_BREAKER_THRESHOLD=3
CERBERUS_CH_BREAKER_WINDOW=10s
CERBERUS_CH_BREAKER_OPEN_INTERVAL=5s
CERBERUS_QUERY_TIMEOUT=3s
CERBERUS_ADMIT_PROM=2
CERBERUS_ADMIT_LOKI=2
CERBERUS_ADMIT_TEMPO=2
CERBERUS_CH_MAX_OPEN_CONNS=4
